Perform Kill Chain Decomposition with Maltego CE
Learning Objectives
By completing this lab, you will:

Install and configure Maltego CE for attack analysis
Map attack stages using the Cyber Kill Chain model
Visualize attack paths and identify critical entry points
Analyze threat actor infrastructure and tactics
Prerequisites
Basic understanding of cybersecurity concepts
Familiarity with Linux command line
Knowledge of network protocols and attack methodologies
Understanding of the Cyber Kill Chain framework
Lab Environment
Al Nafi provides Linux-based cloud machines for this lab. Simply click Start Lab to access your dedicated environment. The provided Linux machine is bare metal with no pre-installed tools, so you will install all required software during the lab.

Task 1: Install and Configure Maltego CE
Subtask 1.1: System Preparation
Update your system and install dependencies:

sudo apt update && sudo apt upgrade -y
sudo apt install -y wget curl openjdk-11-jdk python3 python3-pip
Subtask 1.2: Download and Install Maltego CE
Download Maltego CE:

cd ~/Downloads
wget https://maltego-downloads.s3.us-east-2.amazonaws.com/linux/Maltego.v4.5.0.deb
sudo dpkg -i Maltego.v4.5.0.deb
sudo apt-get install -f
Subtask 1.3: Initial Configuration
Launch Maltego and complete setup:

maltego
Create a free Maltego CE account when prompted
Select Maltego CE (Free) license
Complete the registration process
Install default transform hub transforms
Task 2: Load Attack Data and Identify Kill Chain Stages
Subtask 2.1: Create Sample Attack Scenario
Create a sample attack dataset file:

mkdir ~/maltego_lab
cd ~/maltego_lab
cat > attack_indicators.txt << 'EOF'
# APT Attack Scenario - Financial Institution
# Reconnaissance Phase
target_domain: firstnationalbank.com
target_email: admin@firstnationalbank.com
social_media: linkedin.com/company/first-national-bank

# Weaponization & Delivery
malicious_domain: secure-banking-update.com
phishing_email: security-alert@firstnationalbank.com
attachment: BankingUpdate.pdf.exe

# Exploitation & Installation
c2_server: 192.168.100.50
backdoor: banking_trojan.exe
persistence_registry: HKLM\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Run

# Command & Control
c2_domain: update-server.net
c2_ip: 203.0.113.45
beacon_interval: 300

# Actions on Objectives
target_database: customer_accounts.db
exfil_server: data-backup.org
stolen_records: 50000
EOF
Subtask 2.2: Start New Maltego Investigation
Open Maltego CE
Click New Graph
Save the graph as "Kill_Chain_Analysis"
Subtask 2.3: Map Reconnaissance Stage
Add reconnaissance entities:

Drag Domain entity to graph
Set value to firstnationalbank.com
Right-click domain → Run Transform → To DNS Name
Add Email Address entity: admin@firstnationalbank.com
Add Website entity: linkedin.com/company/first-national-bank
Subtask 2.4: Map Weaponization and Delivery
Add delivery mechanism entities:

Add Domain entity: secure-banking-update.com
Add Email Address entity: security-alert@firstnationalbank.com
Add File entity: BankingUpdate.pdf.exe
Connect entities with Link relationships
Task 3: Visualize Attack Paths and Identify Entry Points
Subtask 3.1: Map Exploitation Phase
Add exploitation indicators:

Add IPv4 Address entity: 192.168.100.50
Add File entity: banking_trojan.exe
Add Registry Key entity: HKLM\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Run
Subtask 3.2: Map Command and Control
Add C2 infrastructure:

Add Domain entity: update-server.net
Add IPv4 Address entity: 203.0.113.45
Run transform: Right-click domain → To IP Address
Add Phrase entity for beacon interval: 300 seconds
Subtask 3.3: Map Actions on Objectives
Add final stage indicators:

Add File entity: customer_accounts.db
Add Domain entity: data-backup.org
Add Phrase entity: 50000 records stolen
Subtask 3.4: Apply Kill Chain Labels
Label each phase:

Select reconnaissance entities
Right-click → Entity Properties → Notes
Add label: Kill Chain Stage: Reconnaissance
Repeat for each stage:
Weaponization
Delivery
Exploitation
Installation
Command & Control
Actions on Objectives
Subtask 3.5: Analyze Attack Flow
Create visual attack flow:

Use Link entities to connect sequential stages
Apply different colors to each kill chain stage:
Reconnaissance: Blue
Weaponization: Orange
Delivery: Red
Exploitation: Purple
Installation: Green
C2: Yellow
Actions: Black
Subtask 3.6: Identify Critical Entry Points
Analyze the graph to identify:

Primary Entry Point: Phishing email delivery
Secondary Entry Points: Social media reconnaissance
Critical Infrastructure: C2 servers and domains
High-Value Targets: Customer database
Create summary analysis:

cat > kill_chain_analysis.txt << 'EOF'
KILL CHAIN DECOMPOSITION ANALYSIS
=================================

ENTRY POINTS IDENTIFIED:
1. Primary: Phishing email (security-alert@firstnationalbank.com)
2. Secondary: Social media reconnaissance (LinkedIn)
3. Infrastructure: Malicious domain (secure-banking-update.com)

CRITICAL ATTACK PATH:
Reconnaissance → Weaponization → Email Delivery → Exploitation → C2 Communication → Data Exfiltration

MITIGATION RECOMMENDATIONS:
- Email security controls for phishing detection
- Domain reputation monitoring
- Network segmentation to prevent C2 communication
- Database access controls and monitoring
- Employee security awareness training

INDICATORS OF COMPROMISE (IOCs):
- Domain: secure-banking-update.com
- IP: 203.0.113.45
- File: BankingUpdate.pdf.exe
- C2 Domain: update-server.net
EOF
Subtask 3.7: Export Analysis Results
Export your Maltego graph:

File → Export → Export Graph as Image
Save as kill_chain_visualization.png
File → Export → Export to CSV
Save entity data as attack_indicators.csv
Verify exported files:

ls -la ~/maltego_lab/
cat attack_indicators.csv | head -10
